Certainly! Below is the Terraform configuration that creates an IAM role, a Redshift cluster, and associates the IAM role with the Redshift cluster. The code is provided in HCL format within a Markdown code block.

```hcl
resource "aws_iam_role" "redshift_role" {
  name = "redshift_role"

  assume_role_policy {
    version = "2012-10-17"
    statement = {
      action    = "sts:AssumeRole"
      principal = {
        service = "redshift.amazonaws.com"
      }
      effect = "Allow"
      sid     = ""
    }
  }
}

resource "aws_redshift_cluster" "example_cluster" {
  cluster_identifier = "example-cluster"
  node_type         = "dc2.large"
  number_of_nodes   = 2
  cluster_class    = "multi-node"

  # Associate the IAM role with the cluster
  iam_roles = [
    {
      iam_role_arn = aws_iam_role.redshift_role.arn
      cluster_role_arn = "arn:aws:redshift:${var.region}:${var.account_id}:clusterrole:iamauth"
    }
  ]
}

# Additional necessary policy association for IAM role to Redshift cluster
resource "aws_iam_policy_attachment" "redshift_cluster_policy" {
  name       = "Redshift-ClusterPolicy"
  policy_arn  = "arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/AmazonRedshiftClusterFullAccess"
  roles      = [aws_iam_role.redshift_role.name]
}
```

In this configuration:

1. An IAM role is created for Redshift with trust relationships allowed from the Redshift service.
2. A Redshift cluster is defined with its identifier, node type, number of nodes, and cluster class.
3. The IAM role is associated with the Redshift cluster to enable IAM authentication.
4. An IAM policy attachment is specified for the Redshift cluster to allow the necessary AWS Redshift cluster access.

Adjust the cluster identifier names and policy ARNs according to your environment and naming conventions. Also, ensure to set appropriate variables to reflect your account ID and region if needed.

