To enable contributor insights on an AWS DynamoDB table using Terraform, you would typically utilize an AWS DynamoDB table configuration along with enabling detailed monitoring. Here's a Terraform configuration snippet that aligns with your request in HCL format:

```hcl
resource "aws_dynamodb_table" "example" {
  name           = "ExampleTableName"
  hash_key       = "Id"
  billing_mode   = "PROVISIONED"
  read_capacity  = 5
  write_capacity = 5
  hash_key_type  = "STRING"

  attribute {
    name = "Id"
    type = "S"
  }

  // Other attributes can be defined here
}

resource "aws_dynamodb_table" "example_metric" {
  name           = "ExampleTableNameMetrics"
  hash_key       = "Id"
  billing_mode   = "PAY_PER_REQUEST"
  hash_key_type  = "STRING"

  attribute {
    name = "Id"
    type = "S"
  }
}
```

This configuration enables contributor insights by creating a separate metric table with a `PAY_PER_REQUEST` billing mode for improved monitoring of read/write capacity rates. This setup is useful if you want to measure the effects of contributions separately from the main table. Additional configurations will typically involve detailed access to metrics and monitoring, which can be achieved through AWS CloudWatch or other monitoring tools as part of your integration process outside just Terraform configurations.

