response:
To configure a custom Time to Live (TTL) attribute for data expiration, you can use Amazon DynamoDB's TTL feature. Below is a Terraform configuration that sets up a DynamoDB table with a custom TTL attribute.

```hcl
resource "aws_dynamodb_table" "example" {
  name           = "example-dynamodb-table"
  hash_key       = "id"
  read_capacity  = 5
  write_capacity = 5
  attribute {
    name = "id"
    type = "S"
  }
  attribute {
    name = "tobe_deleted"
    type = "N"
    attribute_action = "ADD"
  }
}
```

In this configuration, `tobe_deleted` is a numeric attribute that specifies the desired TTL for the items in the DynamoDB table. You can set the TTL in DynamoDB when storing an item by assigning the `tobe_deleted` attribute a timestamp representing the time at which to expire the item. Using Terraform, you can define RDD and CW bucket capacities, as well as other attributes related to your item's structure. The TTL attribute will be automatically handled by DynamoDB once its value is set.

