Here is the Terraform configuration for creating a NAT Gateway associated with a specified subnet and Elastic IP allocation ID, configured for public connectivity:

```hcl
resource "aws_eip" "nat_gateway_eip" {
  vpc = true
}

resource "aws_nat_gateway" "nat_gateway" {
  allocation_id = aws_eip.nat_gateway_eip.id
  subnet_id      = "your-subnet-id" // Replace with your specific subnet ID
}

resource "aws_route" "nat_route" {
  route_table_id = "your-route-table-id" // Replace with your route table ID
  destination_cidr_block = "0.0.0.0/0"
  gateway_id           = aws_nat_gateway.nat_gateway.id
}
```

Make sure to replace `"your-subnet-id"` and `"your-route-table-id"` with the actual IDs of your VPC's subnet and route table, respectively. The NAT Gateway configuration is essential for ensuring that instances within the private subnet of your VPC are able to initiate outbound traffic to the internet while routing inbound traffic to the instance itself.

